content.problemStatement:
The Logical OR operator (`||`) in C++ is used to combine two or more boolean conditions. It returns true if at least one condition is true. If both conditions are false, the result is false.

**Syntax**
```cpp
(condition1) || (condition2)
```
---
**Example**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Test case 1: true || true
    bool case1 = true || true;
    cout << "true || true = " << case1 << endl;  // Output: true || true = 1

    // Test case 2: true || false
    bool case2 = true || false;
    cout << "true || false = " << case2 << endl;  // Output: true || false = 1

    // Test case 3: false || true
    bool case3 = false || true;
    cout << "false || true = " << case3 << endl;  // Output: false || true = 1

    // Test case 4: false || false
    bool case4 = false || false;
    cout << "false || false = " << case4 << endl;  // Output: false || false = 0

    return 0;
}

